<h2>Profiling CSS for fun and profit</h2>

<p>I=E2=80=99ve been recently working on optimizing performance of a so-cal=
led one-page web app. The application was highly dynamic, interactive, and =
was heavily stuffed with new CSS3 goodness. I=E2=80=99m not talking just bo=
rder-radius and gradients. It was a full stack of shadows, gradients, trans=
forms, sprinkled with transitions, smooth half-transparent colors, clever p=
seudo-element -based CSS tricks, and experimental CSS features.</p>

<p>Aside from looking into bottlenecks on Javascript/DOM side, I decided to=
 step into the CSS land. I wanted to see the kind of impact these nice UI e=
lements have on performance. The old version of the app =E2=80=94 the one w=
ithout all the fluff =E2=80=94 was much snappier, even though the JS logic =
behind it hasn=E2=80=99t changed all that drastically. I could see by scrol=
ling and animations that things are just not as quick as they should be.</p=
>

<p>Was styling to blame?</p>

<p>Fortunately, just few days before, Opera folks <a href=3D"http://my.oper=
a.com/dragonfly/blog/style-profiler-preview">came out with an experimental =
=E2=80=9Cstyle profiler=E2=80=9D</a> (followed by WebKit=E2=80=99s ticket+p=
atch <a href=3D"https://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=3D74004">shortly af=
ter</a>). The profiler was meant to reveal the performance of CSS selector =
matching, document reflow, repaint, and even document and css parsing times=
.</p>

<p>Perfect!</p>

<p><img src=3D"http://perfectionkills.com/images/profiler.png" width=3D"900=
px"></p>

<p>I wasn=E2=80=99t thrilled about profiling in one environment, and optimi=
zing according to one engine (especially the engine that=E2=80=99s used onl=
y in one browser), but decided to give it a try. After all, the offending s=
tyles/rules would probably be similar in all engines/browsers. And this was=
 pretty much the only thing out there. </p>

<p>The only other somewhat similar tool was WebKit=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ctimel=
ine=E2=80=9D tab in Developer Tools. But timeline wasn=E2=80=99t very frien=
dly to work with. It wouldn=E2=80=99t show total time of reflow/repaint/sel=
ector matching, and the only way to extract that information was by exporti=
ng data as json and parsing it manually (I=E2=80=99ll get to that later).</=
p>

<p>Below are some of my observations from profiling using both WebKit and O=
pera tools. <a href=3D"http://perfectionkills.com/profiling-css-for-fun-and=
-profit-optimization-notes/#summary">TL;DR version is at the end.</a></p>

<div style=3D"background:#ffe;padding:5px;box-shadow:rgba(0,0,0,0.2) 0 0 3p=
x">
  <p>Before we start, I=E2=80=99d like to mention that most (if not all) of=
 these notes apply best to large, complex applications. Documents that have=
 thousands of elements and that are highly interactive will benefit the mos=
t. In my case, I reduced page load time by ~650ms (~500ms (!) on style reca=
lculation alone, ~100ms on repaint, and ~50ms on reflow). The application b=
ecame noticeably snappier, especially in older browsers like IE7.</p>
  <p>For simpler pages/apps, there are plenty of other optimizations that s=
hould be looked into first.</p>
</div>

<h2 id=3D"notes">Notes</h2>

<ol>

<li><p>The fastest rule is the one that doesn=E2=80=99t exist. There=E2=80=
=99s a common strategy to combine stylesheet =E2=80=9Cmodules=E2=80=9D into=
 one file for production. This makes for one big collection of rules, where=
 some (lots) of them are likely not used by particular part of the site/app=
lication. <strong>Getting rid of unused rules</strong> is one of the best t=
hings your can do to optimize CSS performance, as there=E2=80=99s less matc=
hing to be done in the first place. There are certain benefits of having on=
e big file, of course, such as the reduced number of requests. But it shoul=
d be possible to optimize at least critical parts of the app, by including =
only relevant styles. </p>

<p>This isn=E2=80=99t a new discovery by any means. Page Speed <a href=3D"h=
ttp://code.google.com/speed/page-speed/docs/payload.html#RemoveUnusedCSS">h=
as always been warning against this</a>. However, I was really surprised to=
 see <strong>just how much</strong> this could really affect the rendering =
time. In my case, I shaved ~200-300ms of selector matching =E2=80=94 accord=
ing to Opera profiler =E2=80=94 just by getting rid of unused CSS rules. La=
yout and paint times went down as well.</p></li>

<li><p>Reducing reflows =E2=80=94 another well-known optimization =E2=80=94=
 plays big role here as well. Expensive styles are not so expensive when fe=
wer reflows/repaints need to be performed by the browser. And even simple s=
tyles could slow things down if they=E2=80=99re applied a lot. Reducing ref=
lows AND reducing complexity of CSS go hand in hand.</p></li>

<li><p>Most expensive selectors tend to be universal ones (<code>"*"</code>=
), and those with multiple classes (<code>".foo.bar"</code>, <code>"foo .ba=
r.baz qux"</code>, etc.). We already knew this, but it=E2=80=99s nice to ge=
t confirmation from profilers.</p></li>

<li><p>Watch out for universal selectors (<code>"*"</code>) that are used f=
or =E2=80=9Cno reason=E2=80=9D. I found selectors like <code>"button &gt; *=
"</code>, even though throughout the site/app buttons only had <code>&lt;sp=
an&gt;</code>=E2=80=99s in them. Replacing <code>"button &gt; *"</code> wit=
h <code>"button &gt; span"</code> made for some amazing improvements in sel=
ector performance. The browser no longer needs to <strong>match every eleme=
nt</strong> (due to <a href=3D"https://developer.mozilla.org/en/Writing_Eff=
icient_CSS#How_the_Style_System_Matches_Rules">right-left matching</a>). It=
 only needs to walk over &lt;span&gt;=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94 the number of whi=
ch could be significantly smaller =E2=80=94 and check if parent element is =
&lt;button&gt;. You obviously need to be careful substituting <code>"*"</co=
de> with specific tags, as it=E2=80=99s often hard to find all the places w=
here this selector could be used. </p>

<p>The big downside of this optimization is that you <strong>lose flexibili=
ty</strong>, as changing markup will now require changing CSS as well. You =
won=E2=80=99t be able to just replace one button implementation with anothe=
r one in the future. I felt iffy doing this replacement, as it's essentiall=
y getting rid of useful abstraction for the sake of performance. As always,=
 find the right compromise for your particular case, until engines start to=
 optimize such selectors and we don't have to worry about them.</p></li>

<li><p>I used this snippet to quickly find which elements to substitute <co=
de>"*"</code> with.</p>

<pre lang=3D"javascript"><code>
$$(selector).pluck('tagName').uniq(); // ["SPAN"]</code></pre>

<p>This relies on <a href=3D"http://www.prototypejs.org/api/enumerable/pluc=
k"><code>Array#pluck</code></a> and <a href=3D"http://prototypejs.org/api/a=
rray/uniq"><code>Array#uniq</code></a> extensions from Prototype.js. For pl=
ain version (with reliance on ES5 and selectors API), perhaps something lik=
e this would do:</p>

<pre lang=3D"javascript"><code>
Object.keys([].slice.call(
  document.querySelectorAll('button &gt; *'))
    .reduce(function(memo, el){ memo[el.tagName] =3D 1; return memo; }, {})=
);
</code></pre>
</li>

<li><p>In both Opera and WebKit, <code>[type=3D"..."]</code> selectors seem=
 to be more expensive than <code>input[type=3D"..."]</code>. Probably due t=
o browsers limiting attribute check to elements of specified tag (after all=
, <code>[type=3D"..."]</code> IS a universal selector).</p></li>

<li><p>In Opera, pseudo <code>"::selection"</code> and <code>":active"</cod=
e> are also among more expensive selectors =E2=80=94 according to profiler.=
 I can understand <code>":active"</code> being expensive, but not sure why =
<code>"::selection"</code> is. Perhaps a =E2=80=9Cbug=E2=80=9D in Opera=E2=
=80=99s profiler/matcher. Or just the way engine works.</p></li>

<li><p>In both Opera and WebKit, <code>"border-radius"</code> is <strong>am=
ong the most expensive CSS properties</strong> to affect rendering time. Ev=
en more than shadows and gradients. Note that it doesn=E2=80=99t affect <st=
rong>layout</strong> time =E2=80=94 as one would think =E2=80=94 but mainly=
 <strong>repaint</strong>.</p>

<p>As you can see from <a href=3D"https://github.com/kangax/perfectionkills=
.com/blob/master/css_perf/css_perf_test.html">this test page</a>, I created=
 a document with 400 buttons.</p>

<p><img src=3D"http://perfectionkills.com/images/buttons.png" alt=3D"Button=
s" title=3D""></p>

<p>I started checking how various styles affect rendering performance (=E2=
=80=9Crepaint time=E2=80=9D in profiler). The basic version of button only =
had these styles:</p>

<pre lang=3D"css"><code>
background: #F6F6F6;
border: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
font-size: 14px;
height: 32px;
vertical-align: middle;
padding: 7px 10px;
float: left;
margin: 5px;
</code></pre>

<p><img src=3D"http://perfectionkills.com/images/btn_before.png" alt=3D"Btn=
 Before" title=3D""></p>

<p>The total repaint time of 400 buttons with these basic styles only took =
6ms (in Opera). I then gradually added more styles, and recorded change in =
repaint time. The final version had these additional styles, and was taking=
 177ms to repaint =E2=80=94 a 30x increase!</p>

<pre lang=3D"css"><code>
text-shadow: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.796875) 0px 1px 0px;
box-shadow: rgb(255, 255, 255) 0px 1px 1px 0px inset, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.09765=
63) 0px 2px 3px 0px;
border-radius: 13px;
background: -o-linear-gradient(bottom, #E0E0E0 50%, #FAFAFA 100%);
opacity: 0.9;
color: rgba(0,0,0,0.5);
</code></pre>

<p><img src=3D"http://perfectionkills.com/images/btn_after.png" alt=3D"Btn =
After" title=3D""></p>

<p>The exact breakdown of each one of those properties was as follows:</p>



<p>The text-shadow and linear-gradient were among the least expensive ones.=
 Opacity and transparent rgba() color were a little more expensive. Then th=
ere was box-shadow, with inset one (<code>0 1px 1px 0</code>) slightly fast=
er than regular one (<code>0 2px 3px 0</code>). Finally, the unexpectedly h=
igh border-radius.</p>

<p>I also tried transform with rotate parameter (just 1deg) and got really =
high numbers. Scrolling the page =E2=80=94 with 400 slightly rotated button=
s on it =E2=80=94 was also noticeably jerky. I=E2=80=99m sure it=E2=80=99s =
not easy to arbitrarily transform an element on a page. Or maybe this is th=
e case of lack of optimization? Out of curiosity, I checked different degre=
es of rotation and got this:</p>



<p>Note how even rotating element by 0.01 degree is very expensive. And as =
the angle increases, the performance seems to drop, although not linearly b=
ut apparently in a wavy fashion (peaking at 45deg, then falling at 90deg).<=
/p>

<p>There=E2=80=99s room for so many tests here =E2=80=94 I=E2=80=99d be cur=
ious to see performance characteristics of various transform options (trans=
late, scale, skew, etc.) in various browsers.</p></li>

<li><p>In Opera, <strong>page zoom level affects layout performance</strong=
>. Decreasing zoom increases rendering time. This is quite understandable, =
as more stuff has to be rendered per same area. It might seem like an insig=
nificant detail, but in order to keep tests consistent, it=E2=80=99s import=
ant to make sure zoom level doesn=E2=80=99t mess up your calculations. I ha=
d to redo all my tests after discovering this, just to make sure I=E2=80=99=
m not comparing oranges to grapefruits.</p>

<p>Speaking of zoom, it could make sense to test decreased font and see how=
 it affects overall performance of an app =E2=80=94 is it still usable?</p>=
</li>

<li><p>In Opera, resizing browser window <strong>doesn=E2=80=99t affect ren=
dering performance</strong>. It looks like layout/paint/style calculations =
are not affected by window size.</p></li>

<li><p>In Chrome, resizing browser window <strong>does affect performance</=
strong>. Perhaps Chrome is smarter than Opera, and only renders visible are=
as.</p></li>

<li><p>In Opera, <strong>page reloads negatively affect performance</strong=
>. The progression is visibly linear. You can see from the graph how render=
ing time slowly increases over 40 page reloads (each one of those red recta=
ngles on the bottom correspond to page load followed by few second wait). P=
aint time becomes almost 3 times slower at the end. It looks almost like pa=
ge is leaking. To err on a side of caution, I always used the average of fi=
rst ~5 results to get =E2=80=9Cfresh=E2=80=9D numbers.</p>

<p><img src=3D"http://perfectionkills.com/images/profiler_page_reload.png" =
alt=3D"Profiler Page Reload" style=3D"width:900px"></p>

<p>Script used for testing (reloading page):</p>

<pre lang=3D"javascript"><code>
window.onload =3D function() {
  setTimeout(function() {
    var match =3D location.href.match(/\?(\d+)$/);
    var index =3D match ? parseInt(match[1]) : 0;
    var numReloads =3D 10;
    index++;
    if (index &lt; numReloads) {
      location.href =3D location.href.replace(/\?\d+$/, '') + '?' + index;
    }
  }, 5000);
};
</code></pre>

<p>I haven't checked if page reloads affect performance in WebKit/Chrome.</=
p></li>

<li><p>An interesting offending pattern I came across was a <a href=3D"http=
://sass-lang.com/">SASS</a> chunk like this:</p>

<pre lang=3D"css"><code>
a.remove &gt; * {
  /* some styles */
  .ie7 &amp; {
    margin-right: 0.25em;
  }
}
</code></pre>

<p>..which would generate CSS like this:</p>

<pre lang=3D"css"><code>
a.remove &gt; * { /* some styles */ }
.ie7 a.remove &gt; * { margin-right: 0.25em }
</code></pre>

<p>Notice the additional IE7 selector, and how it has a universal rule. We =
know that universal rules are slow due to right-left matching, and so all b=
rowsers except IE7 (which .ie7 =E2=80=94 probably on &lt;body&gt; element =
=E2=80=94 is supposed to target) are taking an unnecessary performance hit.=
 This is obviously the worst case of IE7-targeted selector.</p>

<p>Other ones were more innocent:</p>

<pre lang=3D"css"><code>
.steps {
  li {
    /* some styles */
    .ie7 &amp; {
      zoom: 1;
    }
  }
}
</code></pre>

<p>..which produces CSS like:</p>

<pre lang=3D"css"><code>
.steps li { /* some styles */ }
.ie7 .steps li { zoom: 1 }
</code></pre>

<p>But even in this case engine needs to check each <code>&lt;li&gt;</code>=
 element (that=E2=80=99s within element with class =E2=80=9Csteps=E2=80=9D)=
 until it would =E2=80=9Crealize=E2=80=9D that there=E2=80=99s no element w=
ith =E2=80=9Cie7=E2=80=9D class further up the tree.</p>

<p>In my case, there was close to a hundred of such .ie7 and .ie8 -based se=
lectors in a final stylesheet. Some of them were universal. The fix was sim=
ple =E2=80=94 move all IE-related styles to a separate stylesheet, included=
 via conditional comments. As a result, there were that many less selectors=
 to parse, match and apply.</p>

<p>Unfortunately, this kind of optimization <strong>comes with a price</str=
ong>. I find that putting IE-related styles next to the original ones is ac=
tually a more maintainable solution. When changing/adding/removing somethin=
g in the future, there=E2=80=99s only one place to change and so there=E2=
=80=99s less chance to forget IE-related fixes. Perhaps in the future tools=
 like SASS could optimize declarations like these out of the main file and =
into conditionally-included ones.</p></li>

<li><p>In Chrome (and WebKit), you can use =E2=80=9CTimeline=E2=80=9D tab i=
n Developer tools to get similar information about repaint/reflow/style rec=
alculation performance. Timeline tab allows you to export data as JSON. Fir=
st time I=E2=80=99ve seen this done was by <a href=3D"http://calendar.perfp=
lanet.com/2011/pure-css3-images-hmm-maybe-later/">Marcel Duran</a> in this =
year=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"http://calendar.perfplanet.com/2011">Performance =
Calendar</a>. Marcel used node.js and a <a href=3D"https://github.com/marce=
lduran/sandbox.javascriptrules.com/blob/gh-pages/purecss3image/rendering/su=
mmary.js">script</a> to parse and extract data.</p>

<p>Unfortunately, his script was including "Recalculate styles" time in the=
 =E2=80=9Clayout=E2=80=9D time =E2=80=94 something I wanted to avoid. I als=
o wanted to avoid page reloads (and getting average/median time). So I twea=
ked it to a much simpler version. It walks over entire data, filtering entr=
ies related to Repaint, Layout, and Style Calculation; then sums up total t=
ime for each of those entries:</p>

<pre lang=3D"javascript"><code>
var LOGS =3D './logs/',
    fs =3D require('fs'),
    files =3D  fs.readdirSync(LOGS);

files.forEach(function (file, index) {
  var content =3D fs.readFileSync(LOGS + file),
      log,
      times =3D {
        Layout: 0,
        RecalculateStyles: 0,
        Paint: 0
      };

  try {
    log =3D JSON.parse(content);
  }
  catch(err) {
    console.log('Error parsing', file, ' ', err.message);
  }
  if (!log || !log.length) return;

  log.forEach(function (item) {
    if (item.type in times) {
      times[item.type] +=3D item.endTime - item.startTime;
    }
  });

  console.log('\nStats for', file);
  console.log('\n  Layout\t\t', times.Layout.toFixed(2), 'ms');
  console.log('  Recalculate Styles\t', times.RecalculateStyles.toFixed(2),=
 'ms');
  console.log('  Paint\t\t\t', times.Paint.toFixed(2), 'ms\n');
  console.log('  Total\t\t\t', (times.Layout + times.RecalculateStyles + ti=
mes.Paint).toFixed(2), 'ms\n');
});
</code></pre>

<p>After saving timeline data and running a script, you would get informati=
on like this:</p>

<pre lang=3D"javascript"><code>
Layout                      6.64 ms
Recalculate Styles          0.00 ms
Paint                       114.69 ms

Total                       121.33 ms
</code></pre>

<p>Using Chrome=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CTimeline=E2=80=9D and this script, I ran=
 original button test that I tested before in Opera and got this:</p>



<p>Similarly to Opera, border-radius was among least performant. However, l=
inear-gradient was comparatively more expensive than that in Opera and box-=
shadow was much higher than text-shadow.</p>

<p>One thing to note about Timeline is that it only provides "Layout" infor=
mation, whereas Opera's profiler has "Reflow" AND "Layout". I'm not sure if=
 reflow data analogous to Opera's is included in WebKit's "Layout" or if it=
's discarded. Something to find out in the future, in order to have correct=
 testing results.</p></li>

<li><p>When I was almost done with my findings, WebKit has added selector p=
rofiler similar to Opera=E2=80=99s one.</p>

<p><img src=3D"http://perfectionkills.com/images/SelectorProfile.png" width=
=3D"900"></p>

<p>I wasn=E2=80=99t able to do many tests with it, but noticed one interest=
ing thing. Selector matching in WebKit was <strong>marginally faster</stron=
g> than that of Opera. The same document =E2=80=94 that one-page app I was =
working on (before optimizations) =E2=80=94 took 1,144ms on selector matchi=
ng in Opera, and only 18ms in WebKit. That=E2=80=99s a ~65x difference. Eit=
her something is off in calculations of one of the engines, or WebKit is re=
ally much much faster at selector matching. For what it=E2=80=99s worth, Ch=
rome=E2=80=99s timeline was showing ~37ms for total style recalculation (mu=
ch closer to WebKit), and ~52ms for repaint (compare to Opera=E2=80=99s 225=
ms =E2=80=9CPaint=E2=80=9D total; different but much closer). I wasn=E2=80=
=99t able to save =E2=80=9CTimeline=E2=80=9D data in WebKit, so couldn=E2=
=80=99t check reflow and repaint numbers there.</p></li>
</ol>

<h3 id=3D"summary" tabindex=3D"0">Summary<a href=3D"http://perfectionkills.=
com/profiling-css-for-fun-and-profit-optimization-notes/#summary">=C2=A7</a=
></h3>

<ul>
<li>Reduce total number of selectors (including IE-related styles: <code>.i=
e7 .foo .bar</code>)</li>
<li>Avoid universal selectors (including unqualified attribute selectors: <=
code>[type=3D"url"]</code>)</li>
<li>Page zoom affects CSS performance in some browsers (e.g. Opera)</li>
<li>Window size affects CSS performance in some browsers (e.g. Chrome)</li>
<li>Page reloads can negatively affect CSS performance in some browsers (e.=
g. Opera)</li>
<li>=E2=80=9Cborder-radius=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ctransform=E2=80=9D are amo=
ng most expensive properties (in at least WebKit &amp; Opera)</li>
<li>=E2=80=9CTimeline=E2=80=9D tab in WebKit-based browsers can shed light =
on total recalc/reflow/repaint times</li>
<li>Selector matching is much faster in WebKit</li>
</ul>

<h3 id=3D"questions" tabindex=3D"0">Questions<a href=3D"http://perfectionki=
lls.com/profiling-css-for-fun-and-profit-optimization-notes/#questions">=C2=
=A7</a></h3>

<p>As I end these notes, I have tons of other questions related to CSS perf=
ormance:</p>

<ul>
<li>Quoted attribute values vs. unquoted ones (e.g. <code>[type=3Dsearch]</=
code> vs <code>[type=3D"search"]</code>). How does this affect performance =
of selector matching?</li>
<li>What are the performance characteristics of <strong>multiple</strong> b=
ox-shadows/text-shadows/backgrounds? 1 text-shadow vs. 3 vs. 5.</li>
<li>Performance of pseudo selectors (:before, :after).</li>
<li>How do different border-radius values affect performance? Is higher rad=
ius more expensive? Does it grow linearly?</li>
<li>Does !important declaration influence performance? How?</li>
<li>Does hardware acceleration influence performance? How?</li>
<li>Are styles similarly expensive in different combinations? (e.g. text-sh=
adow with linear-gradient vs. text-shadow on one-color background)</li>
</ul>

<h3 id=3D"future" tabindex=3D"0">Future<a href=3D"http://perfectionkills.co=
m/profiling-css-for-fun-and-profit-optimization-notes/#future">=C2=A7</a></=
h3>

<p>As our pages/apps become more interactive, the complexity of CSS increas=
es, and browsers start to support more and more =E2=80=9Cadvanced=E2=80=9D =
CSS features, CSS performance will probably become even more important. The=
 existing tools are only scratching the surface. We need the ones for mobil=
e testing and tools in more browsers (IE, Firefox). I <a href=3D"https://bu=
gzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=3D713031">created a ticket for Mozilla</=
a>, so perhaps we=E2=80=99ll see something come out of it soon. I would lov=
e to see CSS performance data exposed via scripting, so that we could utili=
ze it in tools like <a href=3D"http://jsperf.com/">jsperf.com</a> (<a href=
=3D"http://cssperf.com/">cssperf.com</a>?). Meanwhile, there's plenty of te=
sts to be done with existing profilers. So what are you waiting for? ;)</p>
</div>


